{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17606529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17606529"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:12:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:12:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15923"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15923","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15923"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8614"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63186"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8614"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15923"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48637"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8654"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20634"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20638"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63186","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63186"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryonic development, the liver begins to form in week four as an outgrowth from the distal end of the foregut.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the embryological origin of the liver?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Neural crest cells from the ectoderm","Lateral plate mesoderm","Yolk sac endoderm","Splanchnic mesoderm","Hepatic diverticulum from foregut endoderm"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe liver develops from the \u003Cstrong\u003Ehepatic diverticulum\u003C/strong\u003E, which is an outgrowth of the foregut endoderm. This occurs during week four of embryonic development. The diverticulum grows into the septum transversum where it divides into two portions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA larger cranial portion that forms the liver parenchyma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA smaller caudal portion that forms the gallbladder and cystic duct\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be dismissed because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeural crest cells\u003C/strong\u003E contribute to the enteric nervous system but not liver development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral plate mesoderm\u003C/strong\u003E forms the body wall, limb buds and heart.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYolk sac endoderm\u003C/strong\u003E contributes to the primitive gut tube but is not the direct origin of the liver.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESplanchnic mesoderm\u003C/strong\u003E contributes to the gut wall but not the liver parenchyma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The liver develops from the hepatic diverticulum of the foregut endoderm during week four of embryonic development.","The hepatic diverticulum divides into a larger cranial portion (liver) and smaller caudal portion (gallbladder and cystic duct)."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015.","Gilbert SF. Developmental Biology. 6th edition. Sunderland (MA): Sinauer Associates; 2000. Endoderm. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK10107/#"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48637"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15923"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48637","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48637"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-20T10:17:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-20T10:18:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8614"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63186"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4949"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\u